## WebSockets & Real-time Communication

HTTP is request-driven; real-time apps need the server to push data. Three main approaches:

**Long Polling:** Client sends a request; server holds it open until data is available, then responds. Client immediately re-requests. Simple but wastes connections.

**SSE (Server-Sent Events):** Server streams text events over a single persistent HTTP connection. Browser's `EventSource` API handles reconnection automatically. One-directional (server→client).
```javascript
const es = new EventSource('/events');
es.onmessage = e => console.log(e.data);
```

**WebSockets:** Full-duplex TCP channel. Client upgrades via HTTP `Upgrade: websocket` header. Both sides can send at any time.
```javascript
const ws = new WebSocket('wss://api.example.com/ws');
ws.onmessage = e => console.log(e.data);
ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'ping' }));
```

**Socket.io** wraps WebSockets with rooms, namespaces, and automatic fallback to long polling. Use WebSockets for chat, live dashboards, collaborative editing, multiplayer games.

